{{Infobox scientist |name = Mark Mitchell |image = Mark Mitchell.jpg |image_size = 200px |alt = |caption = |birth_date = <!--{{birth year and age|1963}}--><!--{{birth date|yyyy|mm|dd}}--> |birth_place = <!--[[City, State]]--> |death_date = |death_place = |residence = |citizenship = |nationality = [[People of the United States|American]] |ethnicity = |fields = |workplaces = [[Georgia Tech Research Institute]] |alma_mater = [[Georgia Institute of Technology]] (BS, MS) |doctoral_advisor = |academic_advisors = |doctoral_students = |notable_students = |known_for = Antennas and radar research |author_abbrev_bot = |author_abbrev_zoo = |influences = |influenced = |awards = |footnotes = }}
'''Mark A. Mitchell''' is the director of the [[GTRI Applied Concepts Laboratory|Applied Concepts Laboratory]] at the [[Georgia Tech Research Institute]], a position he has held since 2013.<ref name=ACL>{{cite web|url=http://www.gtri.gatech.edu/news/mark-mitchell-named-new-acl-director-gtri|title=Mark Mitchell Named New ACL Director at Georgia Tech Research Institute|publisher=[[Georgia Tech Research Institute]]|accessdate=2014-09-18}}</ref>
==Education== Mitchell received Bachelor of Science in Electrical Engineering and Master of Science in Electrical Engineering degrees from the [[Georgia Institute of Technology]] in 1985 and 1986, respectively. As a student at Georgia Tech, he worked for the campus radio station, [[WREK]], serving terms as music director and programming director during his time there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrek.org/about/history/oldies-tapes/|title=The Current Generation of Oldies Tapes|publisher=[[WREK]]|accessdate=2014-10-02}}</ref>
==Career== Mitchell began working at GTRI in 1987 as a research engineer. During his career, he has been involved with the government teams that developed a number of modern [[phased array]] systems, including the [[THAAD]] radar and the [[Cobra Judy Replacement]] program.<ref name=GTPE>{{cite web|url=http://www.pe.gatech.edu/instructors/mark-mitchell|title=Mark Mitchell|publisher=Georgia Tech Professional Education|accessdate=2014-10-02}}</ref> He undertook key roles in several defense acquisition programs heading several Antenna Integrated Product Team (IPT).<ref name=ACL/> Mitchell was named interim director of the Applied Concepts Laboratory in November 2013 and was later made permanent director.<ref name=ACL/>
