{{Main article|Culture of Peru}}
Peruvian culture is primarily rooted in [[Amerindian]] and Spanish traditions,<ref>Víctor Andrés Belaunde, ''Peruanidad'', p. 472.</ref> though it has also been influenced by various African, Asian, and European ethnic groups. [[Peruvian arts|Peruvian artistic traditions]] date back to the elaborate pottery, textiles, jewelry, and sculpture of [[Pre-Inca cultures]]. The Incas maintained these crafts and made [[Architecture of Peru|architectural]] achievements including the construction of [[Machu Picchu]]. [[Baroque]] dominated colonial art, though modified by native traditions.{{sfn|Bailey|2005|pp=72–74}} During this period, most art focused on religious subjects; the numerous churches of the era and the paintings of the [[Cuzco School]] are representative.{{sfn|Bailey|2005|p=263}} Arts stagnated after independence until the emergence of ''[[Indigenismo]]'' in the early 20th century.<ref>Edward Lucie-Smith, ''Latin American art of the 20th century'', pp. 76–77, 145–146.</ref> Since the 1950s, Peruvian art has been [[Eclecticism in art|eclectic]] and shaped by both foreign and local art currents.{{sfn|Bayón|Concha|Martin|1998|pp=425–428|ps=: In Bayón "Art, 1920–c.1980"}}

===Literature===
[[Peruvian literature]] has its roots in the oral traditions of [[pre-Columbian]] civilizations. Spaniards introduced writing in the 16th century; colonial literary expression included [[chronicle]]s and [[Christian literature|religious literature]]. After independence, [[Costumbrism]] and [[Romanticism]] became the most common literary genres, as exemplified in the works of [[Ricardo Palma]].{{sfn|Bayón|Concha|Martin|1998|pp=37–39|ps=: In Martin "Literature, music and the visual arts, c. 1820–1870"}} In the early 20th century, the ''Indigenismo'' movement produced such writers as [[Ciro Alegría]],{{sfn|Bayón|Concha|Martin|1998|pp=151–152|ps=: In Martin "Narrative since 1920"}} [[José María Arguedas]],{{sfn|Bayón|Concha|Martin|1998|pp=178–179|ps=: In Martin "Narrative since 1920"}} and [[César Vallejo]].{{sfn|Bayón|Concha|Martin|1998|pp=250–253|ps=: In Concha "Poetry 1920–1950"}} During the second half of the century, Peruvian literature became more widely known because of authors such as [[List of Nobel laureates in Literature|Nobel laureate]] [[Mario Vargas Llosa]], a leading member of the [[Latin American Boom]].{{sfn|Bayón|Concha|Martin|1998|pp=186–188|ps=: In Martin "Narrative since 1920"}} [[María Jesús Alvarado Rivera]] was a Peruvian rebel feminist, educator, journalist, writer and social activist who was noted by the National Council of Women of Peru in 1969 as the "first modern champion of women's rights in Peru".<ref name="EncWomSocRef2001">{{cite book|title=Encyclopedia of Women Social Reformers: A-L-v. 2. M-Z|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rpuSzowmIkgC&pg=PA10|accessdate=12 May 2013|year=2001|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-57607-101-4|pages=10}}</ref>

=== Architecture ===
{{Main article|Architecture of Peru}}

===Cuisine===
[[Peruvian cuisine]] is a blend of [[Native American cuisine of South America|Amerindian]] and [[Spanish food]] with strong influences from African, Arab, Italian, Chinese, and Japanese cooking.<ref>[[Tony Custer]], ''The Art of Peruvian Cuisine'', pp. 17–22.</ref> Common dishes include ''[[anticuchos]]'', ''[[ceviche]]'' and ''[[pachamanca]]''. Because of the variety of climates within Peru, a wide range of plants and animals are available for cooking.<ref>[[Tony Custer]], ''The Art of Peruvian Cuisine'', pp. 25–38.</ref> Peruvian cuisine has recently received acclaim due to its diversity of ingredients and techniques.<ref>Embassy of Peru in the United States, [https://web.archive.org/web/20080429211108/http://www.peruvianembassy.us/do.php?p=507 ''The Peruvian Gastronomy'']. Retrieved 27 December 2010.</ref>

===Music===
[[File:Marinera trujillo.jpg|200px|thumb|[[Marinera]] dancers in [[Trujillo, Peru|Trujillo]].]]
[[Peruvian music]] has Andean, Spanish and African roots.<ref>Raúl Romero, "Andean Peru", p. 385–386.</ref> In pre-Hispanic times, musical expressions varied widely from region to region; the ''[[quena]]'' and the ''[[tinya]]'' were two common instruments.<ref>Dale Olsen, ''Music of El Dorado'', pp. 17–22.</ref> Spanish conquest brought the introduction of new instruments such as the guitar and the harp, as well as the development of crossbred instruments like the ''[[charango]]''.<ref>Thomas Turino, "Charango", p. 340.</ref> African contributions to Peruvian music include its rhythms and the ''[[Cajon|cajón]]'', a percussion instrument.<ref>Raúl Romero, "La música tradicional y popular", pp. 263–265.</ref> [[Peruvian folk dances]] include ''[[marinera]]'', ''[[tondero]]'' and ''[[huayno]]''.<ref>Raúl Romero, "La música tradicional y popular", pp. 243–245, 261–263.</ref>

