'''Rodney Celvin Akwensivie''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|r|ɒ|d|n|ɪ}}; born 25 November 1996) is a [[Malaysia|Malaysian]]-[[Ghana|Ghanaian]] professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Centre back|centre back]] for [[PKNS F.C.|PKNS]] in the [[Malaysia Super League]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/sport/football/2017/01/13/sarawak-banking-on-youngsters-to-deliver-the-goods/ |title=Sarawak banking on youngsters to deliver the goods. |website= thestar.com.my |date= 13 January 2016 |accessdate=29 October 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.utusanborneo.com.my/2017/01/20/28-pemain-kibar-cabaran-sarawak-diperkenal|title=28 Pemain kibar cabaran Sarawak diperkenal|work=utusanborneo.com.my |accessdate=29 October 2017}}</ref>
==International career==
===Malaysia U23=== On March 2016, Akwensivie received his first call-up to the [[Malaysia national under-23 football team|Malaysia U23s]] for the centralised training camp as a preparation for friendly match against [[Philippines national under-23 football team|Philippines U23s]] and [[Nepal national under-23 football team|Nepal U23s]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fam.org.my/news/senarai-30-pemain-ke-latihan-pusat-skuad-projek-sukan-sea-2017-bertemu-filipina-b-22-nepal |title=Senarai 30 Pemain Ke Kem Latihan Pusat Skuad Projek Sukan Sea 2017. |last =|first=|date=8 August 2016|website=Football Association of Malaysia Official Website|publisher=Football Association of Malaysia|access-date=29 October 2017}}</ref>Rodney was named in the 20-man [[Malaysia national under-23 football team|Malaysia Squad]] for the [[Football at the 2018 Asian Games – Men's tournament|2018 Asian Games]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fam.org.my/news/senarai-akhir-20-pemain-skuad-b-23-kebangsaan-ke-sukan-asia-2018-di-jakarta-palembang-indonesia|title=Senarai Akhir 20 Pemain Skuad B-23 Kebangsaan ke Sukan Asia 2018 di Jakarta & Palembang, Indonesia|language=Malay|publisher=Football Association of Malaysia|date=12 August 2018|accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref>On 20 August 2018, he made his international debut for [[Malaysia national under-23 football team|Malaysia U23s]] against [[Bahrain national under-23 football team|Bahrain]]. In that match, he came on as a substitute, and Malaysia loss 2-3.
==Personal life== Akwensivie was born in Serian, Sarawak to a [[Bidayuh]] mother and a Ghanaian-Malaysian father.<ref>[https://www.fourfourtwo.com/sg/features/meet-sarawaks-young-defender-who-qualifies-play-malaysia-and-ghana Meet Sarawak's young defender who qualifies to play for Malaysia and Ghana]. ''FourFourTwo''. Retrieved 24 June 2017.</ref> He also has a brother, [[Abbel Akwensivie|Abbel]] who plays for [[Sarawak FA|Sarawak]].
